<paragraph blockId="17.[811,1421,160,356]" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">
<emphasis box="[813,1419,160,184]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="668" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,160,184]" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Identification.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[985,1232,160,184]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="17" pageNumber="668" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ramonense">
<emphasis box="[985,1232,160,184]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Anthurium ramonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized
</emphasis>
by having a rosette-epiphytic habit, conglomerate roots, short petioles, black glandular-punctate blades only on the lower surface and long inflorescences. In the study area this species can be confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Hemsl." authorityName="Hemsl." box="[1159,1348,297,321]" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="17" pageNumber="668" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="salvinii">
<emphasis box="[1159,1263,297,321]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">A. salvinii</emphasis>
Hemsl.
</taxonomicName>
, which differs in having ribbed petioles and cucculate cataphylls.
</paragraph>
