<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="668" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[813,1420,382,577]" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,1103,382,406]" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[1110,1218,382,406]" name="Colombia" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1228,1350,382,406]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry name="Nicaragua" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Nicaragua</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[936,1025,417,440]" name="Panama" pageId="17" pageNumber="668">Panama</collectingCountry>
. This species of wide distribution is common to observe it in the evergreen and semideciduous forests of Cerro Pirre. Generally, it has an epiphytic habit, but when it falls from the branches of the host trees, can develop an accidental terrestrial habit.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
